\begin_layout Standard
The current chapter aims to explain how investments towards positions that
 grant disparate incomes to consumers may change in response to divergence
 in income gaps.
 The representative poor and rich consumers in the model use a part of the
 granted disposable incomes (in absence of any credit line) to invest towards
 gaining positions in a zero-sum game.
 As in the previous version of the model, the wealth accumulated by the
 consumers are reset at a certain period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 - forcing the consumers to start over accumulations after every period
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The reason for the reset at the end of consumer's life-time is merely an
 impossibility to transfer acquired wealth (assisted by position in the
 game) to the progeny.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After introducing the need for reset of assets in the model, we discuss
 the degenerate case of a positional game where consumers maximise accumulated
 assets at an infinite horizon in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Time-Horizon-for-Maximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 After establishing the futility of positional competition with consumers'
 infinite-horizon in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Time-Horizon-for-Maximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we consider the case with myopic consumers in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Assets-Maximising-Functions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 where asset accumulation counts only until the start of the next immediate
 single-period.
 The Nash Equilibrium and the implications for effects of income differences
 on investments (effort) are then discussed in Sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Withdrawal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is worth highlighting that the notion of rich and poor is normative
 in the model and is meant to elaborate how parameters controlling promotion
 and demotion probability functions must satisfy constraints on composition
 of population.
 The particular composition constraint is merely that neither promotions
 nor demotions continue forever in a closed economy.
 More details of the constraint and its implications are discussed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main changes that have been made since the previous version of the model
 are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Time Horizons} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Unlike the previous model where the long-term time-horizons at which
 assets were to be reset were fixed to a two period horizon, the current
 model adopts a more general approach to time-horizons and allows assets
 to reset at a general interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\tau$
\end_inset

 rather than at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2$
\end_inset

.
 While the solution in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 still deals with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=2$
\end_inset

, a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is interpreted in the model as a higher consumer myopia (i.e.
 shorter time-horizon in the positional game).
 As in the previous model, the short-term horizon is one what consumers
 maximise assets over whereas the long-term horizon is one where the assets
 are expected to be reset (due to inability to transfer assets to the progeny).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Asset resets as no bequest} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Unlike the previous model which assumed presence of calamitous risk to
 accumulated assets, the current model interprets the long-term horizon
 (or long-term period) 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as the end-of-life for the consumer.
 The reset of assets only represents the fact that the consumer is unable
 to transfer her accumulated assets to the progeny at the end of her life.
 In this no-bequest model, the consumer thus banks upon entirely on the
 game of social positions at the end of her life-cycle.
 The feature also addresses the issue of dissimilarity between social and
 economic positions - since it is possible for a significant number of players
 (consumers) in the model to achieve a higher socio-economic position in
 the life-time (i.e.
 the long-term period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

) while still failing to transfer their social status to progeny after end-of-li
fe (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BhattacharyaDugar2012CantBuyMeLove"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is discussed in more detail in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Maximisation of Assets accumulated until start of next period} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - Instead of assuming a particular shape of utility function, a closed-form
 solution is discussed with risk-neutral consumers maximising expected assets
 over a short-term period.
 The martingale requirement for expected asset maximisation is discussed
 and the relevant assumptions are made for optimisation of total assets
 over the short-term horizon.
 The effort or investment in the next period is ignored in the short-term
 horizon (which the consumer maximises expected assets over).
 The consumers are thus concerned with asset accumulation only until the
 start of the next short-term period (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Time-Horizon-for-Maximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for further details).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Concave Promotion and demotion functions} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The promotion and demotion functions are assumed to have a concave (rather
 than logistic) form in the model (see the second condition in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Long-term population composition constraint} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - As a normative concern in the model, the population composition constraint
