\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Time-Horizon-for-Maximisation"

\end_inset

Time-Horizon for Maximisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One could consider the short-term horizon over which consumers maximise
 accumulate assets as infinite periods, finite but multiple periods or as
 the interval spanning only the current and next period.
 In the current chapter, we find the interval spanning the current and start
 of next period to be sufficient for our inferences on consumer behaviour
 in positional games.
 As we explain, an infinite horizon leaves the status game inconsequential
 while a multiple-period span poses additional martingale restrictions that
 may limit further generalisations of consumer utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to see that the consumer time-horizon must be finite in a positional
 game - which would be inconsequential if the poor and rich consumers were
 already aware of their infinite-horizon assets.
 More specifically, if there exist long-term evaluations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 of the future assets for poor and rich consumers (respectively), then the
 net addition to the assets through the positional game would be zero in
 the long-term equilibrium.
 In this equilibrium, the poor and rich consumers would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})\mathscr{A}_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))\mathscr{A}_{1}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})\mathscr{A}_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))\mathscr{A}_{2}}{\delta}=\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 - where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are incomes for poorer consumer 1 and richer consumer 2 (respectively),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 represents the time-value of money i.e.
 a discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 are functions for promotion and demotion functions for two respective positions
 (poor and rich) in the game.
 One way this can be achieved is by having 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=\nu_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 when consumers spend all of their income as investment and their economic
 position remains stable (due to promotion and demotion probabilities implied
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})$
\end_inset

 respectively).
 Any other possible solutions must also maintain that no net value is added
 to the long-term values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and thus positional game is inconsequential for either of the consumers.
 The futility does seem at odds with the ubiquity of status competitions
 we see in the real-world.
 Not only does economic history offer numerous instances of seemingly permanent
 (infinite-horizon) income gaps leading to unrest, the idea of maximisation
 of assets at infinite-horizon also leads to well-known paradoxes in consumer
 behaviour (e.g.
 St.
 Petersburg paradox - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While it is possible to consider a general finite multiple-period maximisation,
 the current chapter rejects it in favour of the interval spanning current
 and start of next period as our preference for latter presents itself with
 two clear advantages.
 First, it circumvents the need to ascertain martingale conditions required
 for multiple periods
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is usually performed with a transform to a risk-neutral probability
 measure which ensures the additivity of assets accumulated over multiple
 time periods (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "harrison1981martingales"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with the asset maximising consumer.
 Second, it allows for more general utility functions where the risk-neutrality
 condition as well as the structural assumptions on intertemporal utility
 may be relieved (e.g.
 with risk-aversion).
 This is because the consumers maximise their utility from assets in a span
 extending over one period alone by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Assets-Maximising-Functions"

\end_inset

Assets Maximising Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the consideration of a time-horizon spanning the current and the start
 of next period, we now look at the maximisation of assets by poor and rich
 consumers.
 The particular time-horizon implies that the assets maximised by the consumer
 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 do not include the effort or investment in the next period.
 More specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents the investment (effort) in short-term period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, then the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 does not include 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t+1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,t+1}$
\end_inset

).
 Considering the poorer consumer as consumer 1, the strategy for consumer
 1 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 can be solved by iterations starting with period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and finishing at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The poorer consumer 1 in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 would thus need to maximise the following function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{1,t}-\nu_{1,t}+\frac{W(\nu_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 are the incomes in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 is the effort in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})$
\end_inset

 is the promotion probability in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that at the end-of-life i.e.
 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

, the consumer (a risk-neutral dynast) cannot carry over the accumulated
 assets and must spend everything on the position game - thus letting the
 assets to be augmented in the last period by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{W(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-W(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer1genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer maximises the following function in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
y_{2,t}-\nu_{2,t}+\frac{L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{1,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genoptimfunc}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer 2 i.e.
 the richer consumer would add the following value to her assets in the
 last period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{L(y_{1,t})y_{1,t+1}+(1-L(y_{2,t1}))y_{2,t+1}}{\delta}\label{eq:consumer2genlastperiod}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

