name "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"

\end_inset

Nash Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We impose two restrictions to the above model for discussion of a Nash Equilibri
um solution.
 These are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Long-term Incomes}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - The income in every period to the consumers remains the same in her life-time
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2,t}=y_{1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[1,\tau]$
\end_inset

.
 With same income assumed in every period and with the maximisation of assets
 (rather than a utility that may consider satiation with assets), the asset
 increments at every period except the last period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 are the same.
 More specifically, the consumer behaviour in every period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
\end_inset

 is one where the poorer (or richer) consumer adds 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1,t})y_{2}+(1-W(\nu_{1,t}))y_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu_{2,t})y_{1}+(1-L(\nu_{2,t}))y_{2}$
\end_inset

) in any time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\ne\tau$
