\begin_layout Standard
While being of normative significance, the population composition constraint
 in a closed economy setting does seem useful in explaining status competitions
 within the intertemporal substitution framework 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed intertemporal substitution itself has been argued to be of a normative
 significance (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It may seem at first that equilibrium conditions where rich and poor positions
 are swapped with no net proportional change do not represent real-world
 conditions, such a composition constraint follows from the very existence
 of dynamic rich and poor categories in a population.
 Further, since the normative notions of poor and rich are driven necessarily
 by a certain life-standard that separates poor from the rich, a population
 composition may in fact be implied solely due to existence of such a dynamic
 boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we elaborate on how the boundary is related with population composition,
 consider that the condition of demotions being much less likely than promotion
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu_{1})>>L(\nu_{2})$
\end_inset

 ) - which may seem to represent the state of the real-world better - can
 be maintained in the long-term only if promotions converge to zero.
 A perpetual presence of status competitions implies however that a position-les
s economy - one that is required for there being no promotions - does not
 arise in the long-term.
 Therefore, as long as promotions are not ruled out in the long-term and
 are plausible for consumers, one must consider that promotions are balanced
 by demotions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a normative level, the balance of promotions and demotions may simply
 reflect the changes in life-standards that define poor and rich categories
 in the real-world.
 While the effect of income differences on promotion to demotion ratio is
 explicit in the model (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho_t_solution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), the effects of changes in separation between rich and poor is implicit
 through 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

.
 To consider how 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 may reflect the balance of demotions and promotions, we first discuss the
 long-term periods where promotions dominate and then those where demotions
 dominate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an economy that has experienced too many promotions in a long-term period
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the population composition would witness an evident change in composition
 of rich and poor so that there are more rich and lesser poor.
 More consumers with higher income would mean that the separating line between
 poor and rich would rise in absolute terms (through consumption or saving).
 Thus not only would the promotions be less because of more rich in the
 economy, but the demotions would be implied simply because many of those
 who were rich before would end up becoming poor.
 Such an indirect demotion (due to change in life-standards defining rich
 and poor) is indeed a normative concern but does act to balance the promotions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be argued equivalently that the demotions cannot continue forever
 either as the life-standards fall with more poor in the economy.
 More particularly, if consumers continue to become poor in a declining
 economy, then the separating line between poor and rich would be lowered
 (in absolute terms) as demotions reduce the proportion of rich in the populatio
n - leading to a decline in life-standards.
 This would also mean that some of those who were poor before the decline
 would be considered relatively rich in the new poorer economy.
 Thus indirect promotions may balance demotions caused by fallen life-standards
 to satisfy population composition constraint again.
\end_layout

